##After the city was sealed off, I photographed the ordinary life that the people in the city were trying to maintain

Vicechina  

Function description, different color vision

On January 24, my hometown, Jingzhou, announced the closure of the city. In the morning, trains and buses in the city were suspended. Now, in the middle of February, nearly a month has passed since I returned from Shanghai.

I'm a photographer, and on January 20, I packed my bags and headed home. By then, masks and disinfectant were no longer available at several pharmacies near my home in Shanghai, but even so, I didn't think it was that serious, the approach of the Spring Festival, the memory of the festival fireworks, a jump into the river of Qinshuang, is surrounded by me to go home the prelude, and then think of home alone mother, I did not plan other options.

Jingzhou is two hundred kilometers from Wuhan, where many people study, work and live. After the city was sealed, I stayed at home, except for the necessities of life. Trapped in the home these days, my mother and sick, afraid to go to the hospital, afraid of being infected, she occasionally issued a painful voice, let me be particularly upset.

Over the next few days, my mother wouldn't get out of bed because of pain, and she'd been feeling weak in all her limbs. I watched her take her temperature and read up on the symptoms of a large number of patients with coronavirus. Anxiety turned to anxiety. On January 27th, under my compulsion, my mother and I went to a nearby hospital, which was not as overcrowded as we had imagined. Everything was in order, except for entering the House to take my temperature and checking in, it's just that the doctor's protective equipment and food seem a little rudimentary. The doctor told me that my mother was only ill because of periarthritis of the shoulder.

After some false alarm, I found that my mother and I had never been together like this before. Family Love has returned to the daily living, a vegetable and a meal of concern, which makes us have more feelings and understanding of what we used to take for granted, it's a precious thing in a disaster.

I take my camera with me when I go shopping. It's a habit. I see people wearing masks to buy groceries, exercise in the morning, sell sugar gourds, and do everything they can to keep to the schedule. Sometimes, I would take a detour to the riverbank, where I often swam, and there were citizens standing sparsely along the riverbank, looking out over the Yangtze, and the sound of the water flowing over the river was a way of finding peace in the moment.

One time I met my brother, who was swimming in winter, and I asked him:

"Aren't you afraid to come swimming? "

"Fear, what's the use of being afraid? Rest assured, we are all in good shape for winter swimming. "

"But be careful. "

"The protection is very good, you rest assured, I do not want to hurt others, and then fear, life or go on, " he replied, running to the river flashing Phnom Penh.

In this special Spring Festival, time by all kinds of emotions bomb, I always think, what should I do. Now I know that the answer is to do everything we can to preserve the most precious normal, because it's only in normal times that people can easily discern the absurd.
